Trends in Redwine by Neil Amin

This dataset has 1599 records. It contains data on different red wines. The data set has variables for fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sug ar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, ph, sulphates, and alcohol. The output is the quality of wine. My goal is to find trends between traits of wines that lead to a higher or lower quality wine.

Here we can see basic information about the dataset. We get statistics about the dataset and all 11 variables. X is not a variable but actually is the index of each record in the data. Quality is the output that we will be trying to find trends about.

These are historgrams for all 11 variables and the output (quality). All of the graphs appear to have a somewhat normal distribution except for residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, and total sulfur dioxide. If we limit the x values then we wont have this problem.

If we alter the bin size and the x values that are included we can see more normalized graph. This gets rid of the smaller, outlier values so that we can see the main bulk of records.

With this graph, we can see the majority of the wine falls between quality 5 and 6. This lets gives us the indicator that anything above a 6 in quality is better than average wine. We want to look for trends in what kinds of wine have this better than average rating.

Univariate Analysis

Since we are investigating what characteristics of the wine make a high quality wine. we are going to focus more on the subset of the data with a higher quality. We will also use the subset of low quality wine which is below a quality rating of 3 in order to see if it follows opposite trends which would indicate some correlations. Most of our data was normally distributes from the beginning but it is important that we find the normal distribution of the others by removing the outliers.

The first box plot compares Fixed Acidity vs Quality. I wanted to see if there was a trend between levels of fixed acidity and quality. From looking at these plots it doesnt seem that there is much of a trend.

The second box plot compares Volatile Acidity vs Quality. There appears to be a trend that less volatile acidity tends to have better quality.

The third box plot compares Citric Acid vs Quality. This plot trends the opposite way of volatile acidity in that more citric acid tended to get better ratings.

The fourth plot compares residual sugar with quality. It appears that there is not much trend between residual sugar and quality.

This first plot is pH vs quality. There doesnt appear to be much correlation.

The second plot is sulphates vs quality. It appears that higher sulphates translate to higher quality wine.

The last plot is alcohol vs quality. There is a strong trend between higher alcohol and higher quality.

After conducting Pearsons correlation on all of the data it is clear that alcohol, fixed acidity, citric acid, and sulphates all have positive correlations with quality. This is in contrast to density, total sulfur dioxide, free sulfur, chlorides, total sulfur,and volatile acidity which were negative.

These graphs show the linear regression line when the characteristics are compared to quality. The lines that had the largest slopes were the ones that also happened to have the largest positve correlations.

Bivariate Analysis

My first goal was to use the box plots to figure out what variables had a strong amount of high quality wines. It seemed that a certain few haracteristics (alcohol, fixed acidity, citric acid, and sulphates). I decided to futhur investigate by checking the correlations. It seems the same characteristics had high positive correlations. Next I plotted all of the variables against quality and the ones with the highest slopping regression lines were the same as previously. These few charactertisitcs are going to require more investigation by me.

Multivariate Plots Section

Because alcohol had the strongest correlation, I took my earlier graphs and compared them again with alcohol as a 2nd variable. The dots are shaded different based on the different levels of alcohol in each. It seems that this graph definitely indicates that higher alcohol is definitely correlated with higher quality.

Multivariate Analysis

It is clear from the multivariate analysis that alcohol was the most important factor in determining quality. The other three characteristics all seemed to have a smaller porportional effect on the quality as well.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

I used this graph because it gave me a good initial indication as to what would be considered good wine vs average wine. I noticed that most of the wine feel into a rating of 5,or 6 which meant that anything about 6 could be considered high quality. This bench mark was used for much of my analysis.

Plot Two

Description Two

I chose to include the box plot of alcohol and quality because I felt that it was the first piece of information that caught my eye when trying to find characteristics of high quality wine. The box plots for the higher quality wines tended to fall higher in alcohol content.

Plot Three

Description Three

I chose to add this graph because sulfates had the second highest positive correlation with quality. This gave a look at where high alcohol and high sulfate containing wine ranked in the quality spectrum.

Reflection

I decided to investigate what characteristics of the wine make a high quality wine. After figuring out what a strong rating was using a histogram for quality, my first goal was to use the box plots to figure out what variables had a strong amount of high quality wines. A certain few characteristics (alcohol, fixed acidity, citric acid, and sulphates) stuck out from others based on their plots. I then futhur investigated by checking the correlations of the 11 variables vs quality. I was able to conclude that same characteristics had high positive correlations.

Finally I plotted all of the variables against quality to confirm my findings and once again the variables with the highest slopping regression lines were the same as previously. While looking at these, alcohol in particular also had the strongest trend so I focused in on that by adding alcohol level to all of the points in the other 3 graphs. It became clear from the multivariate analysis that alcohol was the most important factor in determining quality. The other three characteristics all seemed to have a smaller porportional effect on the quality as well.

My biggest obstacle was removing outliers from the data so that I could normalize it. Residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, and total sulfur dioxide were the characteristics that needed to have outliers removed. Another problem I encountered was being able to create box plots with an x value that was continous. I was able to fix this using the group function.

Going forward I think there needs to be an investigation to whether alcohol is causing a random correlation or an actual causation to an increased quality level. I think BAC of the person creating the quality rating should be accounted for if they are making a judgement based on drinking the wine.
